    "narrative": "The Zurich Zebras enter today\u2019s slate with a high-ceiling lineup led by Yordan Alvarez (79.83) and Junior Caminero (75.43). Alvarez is the clear anchor, benefiting from an elite park factor (+14%) and a favorable matchup against Kyle Freeland, while Caminero draws a exploitable arm in Javier Assad, whose 4.83 xERA provides the highest soft-landing spot for our middle-of-the-order power. Trea Turner (69.09) and Kyle Schwarber (68.72) also provide strong stability, both capitalizing on the matchup against Robbie Ray. While Ray is a veteran presence, the wind conditions at the venue provide a 5% boost to output, effectively neutralizing the inherent risk of his strikeout profile and allowing Turner to leverage his elite speed in a top-of-the-order slot.\n\nThe most difficult roster decision involved the final outfield and utility spots, with Caleb Durbin (47.39) narrowly missing the cut. Despite his utility, Durbin was relegated to the bench primarily due to the strength of Victor Scott II (52.99) and Pete Crow-Armstrong (59.64). In a 5x5 format where stolen bases are at a premium, the optimizer prioritized the projected plate appearance volume and dynamic platoon advantages offered by Scott and PCA over Durbin\u2019s neutral setup. We are tracking several lineup risks today, specifically the reliance on projected batting orders; the Zebras\u2019 scoring efficiency is heavily leveraged on hitters like Yelich (41.21) and Dingler (43.30) maintaining their spots in the lineup. Should those orders shift downward, their marginal scores risk dropping below the 40-point floor, potentially necessitating an mid-game adjustment to preserve our seasonal game caps.",
